 {"id":"br-aazao","title":"Verification Coverage Program: real-path unit tests, E2E completeness, and forensic logging","description":"# Verification Coverage Program: Real-Path Unit Tests, E2E Completeness, and Forensic Logging\n\n## Why\nThe repository already has a large amount of testing surface area, but it would be inaccurate to claim any of the following today:\n- full unit coverage across the workspace\n- zero reliance on mocks, stubs, fake binaries, fake repos, or synthetic fixtures\n- complete end-to-end coverage across every critical workflow and failure mode\n- uniformly excellent, information-dense logging and artifact capture across all E2E suites\n\nCurrent evidence for those gaps is already visible in-tree:\n- deterministic stub encoder coverage in `crates/mcp-agent-mail-core/tests/toon_integration.rs`\n- stub embedder / stub engine coverage in search-core and DB search-bridge tests\n- stubbed LLM completions in `crates/mcp-agent-mail-tools/src/llm.rs`\n- mock release artifacts in `tests/e2e/test_idempotency.sh`\n- fake repo / fake lock / synthetic owner-state scenarios in storage tests\n- wrapper-style E2E entrypoints where artifact richness and logging density are not guaranteed to be identical suite-to-suite\n\n## Goal\nCreate a disciplined verification program that:\n- maps every important module and workflow to concrete tests\n- maximizes real-path coverage rather than simulated-only confidence\n- explicitly documents any remaining sanctioned substitutes that cannot yet be removed\n- standardizes E2E artifact capture, logging density, and rerun breadcrumbs\n- installs CI gates so future contributors cannot quietly regress realism or coverage\n\n## Deliverables\n- repo-wide audit of test coverage, realism, and logging quality\n- policy for what counts as acceptable test realism and when substitutes are allowed\n- burn-down plan for fake-only critical-path tests\n- granular unit-coverage closure across crate clusters\n- granular E2E matrix closure across transport, workflow, failure, and performance paths\n- forensic artifact and logging contract for all E2E suites\n- CI/reporting/sign-off layer for maintaining the standard\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- a future maintainer can answer, with evidence rather than vibes, which critical paths are covered by real-path unit tests, which are covered by E2E, which still rely on sanctioned substitutes, and why\n- no critical user-visible or operator-visible path is validated only by ad hoc stubs or thin happy-path E2E wrappers\n- failures produce enough structured data to debug without blind reruns\n- the resulting bead tree is self-contained enough that implementation can proceed without needing to reconstruct this reasoning from chat history\n\n## Important Notes\nThis is a repo-wide verification hardening program, not a single test bead. The point is to turn broad but uneven coverage into trustworthy and explainable coverage.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":0,"created_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:02.708072106Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:02.708072106Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","e2e","logging","repo-wide","testing","verification"]}
-{"id":"br-aazao.1","title":"Verification Coverage 1.1: repo-wide audit of test realism, gaps, and ownership","description":"# Verification Coverage 1.1: Repo-Wide Audit of Test Realism, Gaps, and Ownership\n\n## Why\nBefore adding more tests, the project needs an explicit inventory of what is already covered, how that coverage is achieved, and where confidence is artificially inflated by substitutes, wrappers, or fixture-only paths.\n\n## Deliverables\n- enumerate the workspace by crate, major module cluster, and critical workflow surface\n- map each surface to existing unit, property, integration, conformance, and E2E coverage\n- classify each test by realism grade:\n  - real-path / real dependency\n  - deterministic local fixture\n  - sanctioned substitute\n  - mock / fake / stub\n  - untested\n- identify which tests are merely contract or formatting tests versus true behavioral tests\n- identify ownership / expected home for missing tests so the backlog is implementable\n- produce a prioritized gap ledger that distinguishes critical-path gaps from cosmetic gaps\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- future beads can point back to this issue as the canonical inventory rather than rediscovering the current state\n- the audit explicitly calls out present realism exceptions such as stub encoders, stub embedders, stub LLM completions, mock installer artifacts, and fake filesystem/repo state tests\n- the audit is specific enough to drive per-subsystem implementation work without hand-wavy “add more tests” follow-ups\n\n## Important Notes\nThis is not a paper exercise. The output must be actionable enough that later beads can close gaps mechanically.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":240,"created_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:02.997462159Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:02.997462159Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","e2e","repo-wide","testing","unit-tests","verification"],"depen